The biosorption of AR88 contaminant from the aqueous solution by the organic adsorbent Acacia dealbata Link. pollen powder (ADL) was studied in detail, in order to predict the amount of AR88 removed through adsorption process. The adsorption process was performed under constant agitation of a 75 mL aqueous solution, by a L32 Basic Hotplate Magnetic Stirrer (Labinco, Breda, Netherlands). The pollen was added to the aqueous solution and the samples were withdrawn at time 0, 5, 10, 15, 20, 25 and 30 min (Fig. 1). The biosorption batch experiments were carried out in three different steps, under fixed conditions (T = 298 K, V = 75 mL, agitation = 350 rpm, t = 30 min):
variation of the pH conditions (3.0–9.0), with [AR88] = 50 mg L−1, [pollen] = 3.0 g L−1;
variation of the pollen dosage (1.5–10 g L−1), with pH 3.0, [AR88] = 50 mg L−1;
variation of the contaminant AR88 concentration (0–500 mg L−1), with pH 3.0, [pollen] = 3.0 g L−1.Fig. 1
Schematic setup of adsorption and UV-A-Fenton process

