In order to degrade the AR88, it was necessary to understand which were the best oxidation processes. Therefore, in this section it were conducted several trials: (1) H2O2, (2) UV-A, (3) UV-A + H2O2, (4) UV-A + Fe2+, (5) Fenton, (6) UV-A-Fenton. From the results obtained (Fig. 7), it is possible to observe that AR88 was resistant to degradation by application of H2O2, UV-A, UV-A + H2O2 and UV-A + Fe2+. Clearly, the oxidation potential of these processes is insufficient to promote the degradation of AR88 and, therefore, no generation of hydroxyl radicals (HO·) takes place. With the Fenton and UV-A-Fenton process it was observed a higher AR88 removal (63.1 and 91.4%, respectively). The Fenton process achieves an AR88 removal due to a high production of HO· radicals, however, the conversion of Fe3+ to Fe2+ is low making its efficiency limited. With the application of UV-A radiation, this limitation is overcome, because the UV radiation regenerates the Fe3+ to Fe2+. The Fe(HO)2+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
